problem:
Two convex quadrilaterals are called partners if they have three vertices in common and they can be labeled $A B C D$ and $A B C E$ so that $E$ is the reflection of $D$ across the perpendicular bisector of the diagonal $\overline{A C}$. Is there an infinite sequence of convex quadrilaterals such that each quadrilateral is a partner of its successor and no two elements of the sequence are congruent?

[asy]
size(200); // Set the size of the output image

// Define the vertices of the diagram
pair A = (0.9,-3);
pair B = (-3, -1.4);
pair C = (-1.1, 2.95);
pair D = (1.6, 2.5);
pair E = (2.8,-1);
pair F = (-1.05,-0.3);
pair G = (4,1.3);

// Draw the diagram
draw(A--B--C--D--A, linewidth(1));
draw(C--E--A, linewidth(1));
draw(C--A, dotted);

// Label the vertices
label("$A$", A, S);
label("$B$", B, W);
label("$C$", C, N);
label("$D$", D, NE);
label("$E$", E, E);

// Create a right angle symbol at intersection of CA and FG
pair H = (0.17,0.1);
pair I = (0.08,0.35);
pair J = (-0.2,0.25);

// Draw the right angle symbol
draw(F--G, dotted);
draw(H--I--J, linewidth(0.5));
[/asy]
